1
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:04,561
My lord, time is short.
leave now, l beg you.

2
00:01:04,737 --> 00:01:06,432
you'll be arrested.

3
00:01:06,605 --> 00:01:08,232
fetch some candles.

4
00:01:09,241 --> 00:01:10,708
l'll be working late.

5
00:01:11,510 --> 00:01:13,705
and my usual glass of wine.

6
00:01:18,017 --> 00:01:20,281
this world had to xhange,

7
00:01:21,420 --> 00:01:24,651
but the revolution is now
a terror sweeping the land,

8
00:01:24,790 --> 00:01:28,248
and it's my turn to be swept aside,

9
00:01:30,162 --> 00:01:34,064
old prejudixes make men blind,
drive them mad,,,

10
00:01:35,134 --> 00:01:39,070
devour their hearts
and turn them into beasts,

11
00:03:11,096 --> 00:03:13,564
ln the year 1764,

12
00:03:13,899 --> 00:03:17,460
the beastreaxhed our soil
and made it its own,

13
00:03:18,203 --> 00:03:23,106
a year later, its fame had spread
beyond the borders of our provinxe,

14
00:03:23,375 --> 00:03:27,744
and it seemed no mortal
would ever overxo me it,

15
00:03:27,880 --> 00:03:29,848
the beast's assaults

16
00:03:30,249 --> 00:03:34,345
slowly sank the region of gevaudan
into darkness,

17
00:04:44,289 --> 00:04:45,415
who goes there?

18
00:06:20,586 --> 00:06:21,951
what's he done?

19
00:06:23,689 --> 00:06:25,316
- what?
- he's a thief.

20
00:06:28,493 --> 00:06:29,425
and her?

21
00:06:29,561 --> 00:06:32,086
his daughter. damned witch !

22
00:06:32,965 --> 00:06:35,593
l healed their horses. they owe me.

23
00:06:35,934 --> 00:06:38,129
don't listen. they're liars!

24
00:06:38,303 --> 00:06:40,168
- did he heal the horses?
- yes.

25
00:06:53,185 --> 00:06:54,243
begone!

26
00:07:18,410 --> 00:07:22,779
welcome to the land of the beast!
beware of wolf traps!

27
00:07:25,884 --> 00:07:27,909
sir gregoire de fronsax

28
00:07:28,186 --> 00:07:32,953
and the man they xalled mani
were neither hunters nor soldiers,

29
00:07:33,091 --> 00:07:38,154
a naturalist at the king's garden,
fronsax was a libertine

30
00:07:38,330 --> 00:07:39,854
and a fine wit,

31
00:07:40,198 --> 00:07:42,564
the man who shadowed him

32
00:07:42,901 --> 00:07:46,268
was a mysterious foreigner,

33
00:07:48,373 --> 00:07:52,901
at nightfall, the travelers arrived
at the xastle of marquis d'apxher,

34
00:07:53,412 --> 00:07:57,849
their protextorin gevaudan
for the duration of their mission,

35
00:08:26,445 --> 00:08:31,382
our people fear no ordinary wolf.
the beast is different.

36
00:08:32,317 --> 00:08:35,548
lt flees men
as if it knew to fear them,

37
00:08:35,687 --> 00:08:37,951
yet spares no woman or child.

38
00:08:38,090 --> 00:08:39,955
have you ever seen it?

39
00:08:40,892 --> 00:08:43,861
how do you know it's just one animal?

40
00:08:43,995 --> 00:08:46,964
the survivors all say the same.

41
00:08:47,499 --> 00:08:51,333
lt's bigger than a wolf
and has no fear of fire arms.

42
00:08:51,903 --> 00:08:54,394
l understand your skepticism.

43
00:08:55,707 --> 00:08:59,040
l don't believe any more than you
in dragons.

44
00:08:59,177 --> 00:09:01,771
l've had a report drawn up,

45
00:09:02,080 --> 00:09:05,846
a memoir of the beast's crimes.

46
00:09:06,885 --> 00:09:08,648
judge for yourself.

47
00:09:12,324 --> 00:09:15,521
you battled the english in new france?

48
00:09:15,994 --> 00:09:19,953
yes, l went to study animals and nature.

49
00:09:21,032 --> 00:09:24,433
l returned with wounds
and a captain's rank.

50
00:09:27,005 --> 00:09:30,907
l've organized a hospital
for victims of the beast,

51
00:09:31,076 --> 00:09:33,101
in an old priory.

52
00:09:34,513 --> 00:09:36,378
a woman from lorciere.

53
00:09:36,815 --> 00:09:40,216
the beast attacked her
coming from the fair.

54
00:09:40,352 --> 00:09:44,982
two men saved her, the beast fled,
but took half her face.

55
00:09:46,658 --> 00:09:50,560
tell me, how is M. buffon?

56
00:09:51,496 --> 00:09:53,191
and how fares paris?

57
00:09:57,235 --> 00:09:59,829
and l'lngenu? have you read it?

58
00:10:00,005 --> 00:10:03,168
lt's a bit late to discuss philosophy.

59
00:10:03,341 --> 00:10:06,401
quite right. let's speak of theater.

60
00:10:06,578 --> 00:10:11,345
do you know any actresses?
what's in the theater this winter?

61
00:10:11,950 --> 00:10:13,247
put it there.

62
00:10:13,385 --> 00:10:18,288
they are a gallant lot, it's said.
l've read some are free with their charms.

63
00:10:18,924 --> 00:10:20,186
do tell me.

64
00:10:24,930 --> 00:10:27,364
here, to satisfy your curiosity.

65
00:10:27,499 --> 00:10:32,266
the merxure de franxe!
we only get the courrier d'avignon,

66
00:10:32,771 --> 00:10:35,604
- l'll show you the common room.
- he'll stay here.

67
00:10:35,740 --> 00:10:38,106
very well. good night, sir.

68
00:10:44,216 --> 00:10:47,049
lt's not versailles, but the wine's good.

69
00:11:48,713 --> 00:11:50,340
lt's big as a cow.

70
00:11:54,185 --> 00:11:58,622
jacques says he's seen many wolves.
lt's no wolf.

71
00:11:58,757 --> 00:12:01,885
lts snout is longer,
its teeth are like knives.

72
00:12:09,668 --> 00:12:14,298
- lf not a wolf, what was it then?
- a demon.

73
00:12:14,739 --> 00:12:18,766
chevalier, the beast has struck
near st. alban.

74
00:12:41,600 --> 00:12:42,532
there.

75
00:12:43,435 --> 00:12:45,460
there's no one there.

76
00:12:45,604 --> 00:12:46,571
halt!

77
00:12:48,073 --> 00:12:51,042
what are those bastards doing here?

78
00:12:51,376 --> 00:12:52,741
good day, captain.

79
00:12:53,979 --> 00:12:57,710
good day, Marquis. My respects.

80
00:12:58,283 --> 00:13:00,615
beware. there are traps.

81
00:13:01,586 --> 00:13:05,750
duhamel, sir gregoire de fronsac
of the king's gardens.

82
00:13:06,591 --> 00:13:11,528
he'd like to examine her body,
with your permission, of course.

83
00:13:12,564 --> 00:13:15,431
the one who brutalized my men?

84
00:13:15,800 --> 00:13:19,395
- had l known you ordered--
- l did not.

85
00:13:20,338 --> 00:13:23,398
you did well, and l beg your pardon.

86
00:13:24,042 --> 00:13:27,671
they're soldiers trained for war,
not hunting.

87
00:13:28,913 --> 00:13:31,973
careful, she's stuffed with poison.

88
00:13:41,960 --> 00:13:44,224
what sort of gardener are you?

89
00:13:44,362 --> 00:13:49,299
when the beast is killed,
his Majesty wants it studied in paris.

90
00:13:49,768 --> 00:13:53,226
l'll keep it after it's captured.

91
00:13:53,672 --> 00:13:55,299
l'm having a look.

92
00:13:58,443 --> 00:14:02,209
with that jaw,
it must weigh 500 pounds.

93
00:14:02,881 --> 00:14:04,746
this time, l'll get it...

94
00:14:05,350 --> 00:14:07,215
before the snow.

95
00:14:07,585 --> 00:14:09,917
lt can't get away.

96
00:14:10,055 --> 00:14:12,148
- ever seen it?
- once.

97
00:14:12,724 --> 00:14:16,751
once, in my musket sight.
l wounded it, my word on it.

98
00:14:16,895 --> 00:14:19,625
lt collapsed, then at once revived.

99
00:14:19,764 --> 00:14:23,894
we lost it near Mt. Mouchet,
vanished in the wood.

100
00:14:24,836 --> 00:14:26,701
did it look like this?

101
00:14:29,541 --> 00:14:33,568
lt had a black stripe
and spike on its back.

102
00:14:48,660 --> 00:14:53,597
My friends, this is the sketch artist,

103
00:14:54,165 --> 00:14:56,531
sir gregoire de fronsac.

104
00:14:57,135 --> 00:15:00,229
a man of providence indeed,
come from paris to--

105
00:15:00,371 --> 00:15:01,497
sketch the beast.

106
00:15:02,107 --> 00:15:05,235
his eminence, the bishop de Mende,

107
00:15:05,543 --> 00:15:07,443
the duke de Moncan,

108
00:15:07,579 --> 00:15:10,013
the count de Morangias,

109
00:15:10,715 --> 00:15:12,706
and Madame the countess.

110
00:15:13,051 --> 00:15:17,511
their son, jean-francois,
who has also traveled.

111
00:15:19,724 --> 00:15:23,160
- a clever hand, sir.
- thank you, sir.

112
00:15:27,499 --> 00:15:30,366
M. laffont, our intendant.

113
00:15:31,102 --> 00:15:34,435
father henri sardis of st. alban's.

114
00:15:39,177 --> 00:15:43,273
tell us, sir, is there talk
of the beast in paris?

115
00:15:43,982 --> 00:15:47,713
- they've written ballads.
- prayers would do better!

116
00:15:47,852 --> 00:15:50,548
does capt. duhamel so need god?

117
00:15:50,822 --> 00:15:52,380
don't we all?

118
00:15:52,857 --> 00:15:56,224
duhamel just dresses his men as women

119
00:15:56,361 --> 00:15:58,295
to bait the beast.

120
00:15:58,763 --> 00:16:00,890
he's doing what he can.

121
00:16:01,065 --> 00:16:02,657
such indulgence!

122
00:16:03,334 --> 00:16:05,325
duhamel is incompetent.

123
00:16:05,470 --> 00:16:09,099
his hunts exhaust the people,
his ruffians devastate our land,

124
00:16:09,274 --> 00:16:11,435
and the beast roams free.

125
00:16:11,609 --> 00:16:16,046
lf duhamel is all l get
for paying my taxes to paris,

126
00:16:16,581 --> 00:16:19,106
l'd rather give it to my valets.

127
00:16:19,517 --> 00:16:23,419
- what do you say, sir?
- you're not obliged to reply.

128
00:16:23,555 --> 00:16:27,082
his lordship likes to argue,
but he's a good christian.

129
00:16:27,225 --> 00:16:31,184
when you arrived,
this assembly was talking my ears off

130
00:16:31,329 --> 00:16:33,388
with god this and god that.

131
00:16:33,531 --> 00:16:37,023
lt's said the pope sent a spy to see

132
00:16:37,168 --> 00:16:40,831
if the beast is
a manifestation of the devil.

133
00:17:05,230 --> 00:17:06,390
pardon me.

134
00:17:14,706 --> 00:17:19,234
Marianne de Morangias.
a daunting task indeed.

135
00:17:19,577 --> 00:17:21,704
the most elusive quarry in our land.

136
00:17:22,113 --> 00:17:26,243
- who's the hapless hunter?
- des forets, a playwright.

137
00:17:27,118 --> 00:17:31,145
- then it's simple.
- careful, she's a Morangias.

138
00:17:35,827 --> 00:17:37,852
sir, we were conferring--

139
00:17:37,996 --> 00:17:40,021
- M. des forets?
- himself.

140
00:17:40,164 --> 00:17:43,531
an honor. good writers are rare.

141
00:17:43,668 --> 00:17:45,465
Marquis d'apcher spoke of you.

142
00:17:46,104 --> 00:17:48,766
he thought of you for his memoirs.

143
00:17:48,940 --> 00:17:49,872
really?

144
00:17:50,008 --> 00:17:53,205
he's in good spirits.
but have some finesse.

145
00:17:53,378 --> 00:17:57,212
wait till he broaches the subject.

146
00:17:58,182 --> 00:17:59,410
excuse me.

147
00:18:01,286 --> 00:18:04,119
- have you no shame?
- none.

148
00:18:05,290 --> 00:18:08,350
does the naturalist like our country?

149
00:18:08,493 --> 00:18:12,930
l've only glimpsed its beauties so far,
or one of them.

150
00:18:14,232 --> 00:18:16,530
ls such the talk of court?

151
00:18:17,268 --> 00:18:20,999
no, this is a couplet
reserved for provincials.

152
00:18:21,940 --> 00:18:25,876
l might go to court
if there were ladies like you.

153
00:18:27,512 --> 00:18:30,504
dinner is served. let's go in.

154
00:18:31,082 --> 00:18:32,845
whither thou goest...

155
00:18:35,720 --> 00:18:40,089
ln sailing up the st. lawrence
we found in our nets

156
00:18:40,291 --> 00:18:43,419
the strangest animal l'd ever seen.

157
00:18:44,062 --> 00:18:46,360
l'd heard of the native's sacred fish,

158
00:18:46,497 --> 00:18:49,432
but l was sure it was a legend.

159
00:18:50,435 --> 00:18:52,699
l was looking at a fish

160
00:18:52,837 --> 00:18:56,102
the shape and size of a trout,

161
00:18:56,975 --> 00:19:01,878
but which was entirely covered
in a rich black fur.

162
00:19:03,481 --> 00:19:06,143
a furry trout? surely you jest.

163
00:19:06,284 --> 00:19:07,308
no, sir.

164
00:19:20,865 --> 00:19:24,130
salmo truta dermopilla from canada.

165
00:19:25,236 --> 00:19:26,828
soft as mink.

166
00:19:32,944 --> 00:19:37,210
- nature is extraordinary!
- the water must be cold!

167
00:19:37,582 --> 00:19:40,676
this proves the impossible
may be possible.

168
00:19:40,818 --> 00:19:41,750
well said.

169
00:19:42,020 --> 00:19:45,251
lt surely won you the king's favor.

170
00:19:45,390 --> 00:19:47,517
l doubt he deserves it.

171
00:19:47,992 --> 00:19:51,359
though l do recognize
your comedic talent.

172
00:19:51,863 --> 00:19:54,331
had l two hands, l'd applaud.

173
00:19:56,968 --> 00:20:00,802
- please pardon him.
- your son is right.

174
00:20:01,739 --> 00:20:04,037
this animal doesn't exist.

175
00:20:04,609 --> 00:20:07,373
My taxidermist is a clever man.

176
00:20:07,912 --> 00:20:09,743
please excuse the prank.

177
00:20:10,181 --> 00:20:14,140
should this fable convince us
there is no beast?

178
00:20:14,285 --> 00:20:16,310
that we're simpletons?

179
00:20:16,521 --> 00:20:18,512
the moral of the fable

180
00:20:18,656 --> 00:20:21,989
is that dragons and unicorns
only appear in fables.

181
00:20:22,360 --> 00:20:25,727
lies appear true when dressed in latin.

182
00:20:25,863 --> 00:20:29,697
careful, sir. we may lose
all sense of what you're saying.

183
00:20:30,168 --> 00:20:33,604
lndeed, are you a naturalist
or a philosopher?

184
00:20:33,738 --> 00:20:35,672
or worse, an actor!

185
00:20:35,807 --> 00:20:38,901
l believe the knight is,
above all, parisian.

186
00:20:39,077 --> 00:20:42,672
enough talk of the beast.
after all, it only preys on peasants.

187
00:20:42,847 --> 00:20:45,816
how about a guessing game? charades?

188
00:20:45,983 --> 00:20:50,716
l've just composed a lover's lament.
May l, countess?

189
00:20:50,988 --> 00:20:53,889
- lf it isn't licentious.
- oh no.

190
00:20:54,125 --> 00:20:56,423
lt's very chaste and pure.

191
00:20:56,561 --> 00:20:59,121
lt's an improvisation.

192
00:20:59,263 --> 00:21:02,255
lt's called ''wolves howl''.

193
00:21:08,306 --> 00:21:12,766
''l went not warily
though l bore no malice, verily

194
00:21:13,444 --> 00:21:17,005
''your sly eye caught my heart
in its prowl

195
00:21:17,448 --> 00:21:21,043
''l howl''

196
00:21:35,633 --> 00:21:37,464
shall l see you soon?

197
00:21:37,602 --> 00:21:40,036
have you other amazing animals to show me?

198
00:21:40,171 --> 00:21:45,074
you seem set in your idea of me.
allow me to change your mind.

199
00:21:45,209 --> 00:21:46,403
try.

200
00:21:47,512 --> 00:21:50,310
- coming to the hunt?
- certainly.

201
00:21:50,848 --> 00:21:54,147
l can't allow it. too dangerous.

202
00:21:55,219 --> 00:21:58,450
obedience is the virtue
of well-born girls.

203
00:21:58,589 --> 00:22:00,819
this young man is right.

204
00:22:05,596 --> 00:22:07,723
that dayin gevaudan,

205
00:22:08,132 --> 00:22:11,260
there was the greatesthunt
everin franxe,

206
00:22:12,336 --> 00:22:16,295
the king offered 6,000pounds bounty
for the beast,

207
00:22:16,474 --> 00:22:19,637
thousands ofenlistedpeasants,
swordsmen and soldiers

208
00:22:19,810 --> 00:22:23,439
werejoined by everyhunter
and adventurerin the region,

209
00:22:24,148 --> 00:22:28,949
for a fewhours,
we forgot we were the hunted,

210
00:23:30,881 --> 00:23:35,147
you each have a map and a location.
Movements begin at 7:00.

211
00:23:35,286 --> 00:23:36,218
thank you.

212
00:23:36,354 --> 00:23:39,915
you might well thank us!
My people have better things to do.

213
00:23:40,057 --> 00:23:42,787
your generosity rivals your courage.

214
00:23:42,927 --> 00:23:46,419
enough ! for your sake,
we'd better take it.

215
00:23:46,564 --> 00:23:49,124
we shall, your lordship.

216
00:23:51,636 --> 00:23:53,467
what is this ruckus?

217
00:27:09,333 --> 00:27:11,233
fine weapon, isn't it?

218
00:27:11,368 --> 00:27:14,496
l had it made in Mende after a campaign.

219
00:27:14,638 --> 00:27:17,505
custom-made for me, of course.

220
00:27:20,077 --> 00:27:24,275
look. even in paris
you'll never see such a bullet.

221
00:27:24,415 --> 00:27:26,110
l make them myself.

222
00:27:26,250 --> 00:27:28,718
silver? afraid of werewolves?

223
00:27:30,888 --> 00:27:33,356
l like to sign my shots.

224
00:27:33,824 --> 00:27:37,885
l'm a hunter, fronsac.
and it has cost me dearly.

225
00:27:38,295 --> 00:27:39,922
how did it happen?

226
00:27:40,397 --> 00:27:44,925
l learned the hard way
that one bullet won't always suffice.

227
00:27:45,069 --> 00:27:49,938
and, sardis notwithstanding,
prayer won't cure gangrene.

228
00:27:50,374 --> 00:27:53,366
- did a bear injure you?
- a lion.

229
00:27:54,879 --> 00:27:58,212
yes, two years in the navy,
l traveled a lot.

230
00:27:58,349 --> 00:28:00,249
do you know africa?

231
00:28:01,151 --> 00:28:04,018
My lords, my daughter caused all this.

232
00:28:04,154 --> 00:28:06,748
here. punish her as you will.

233
00:28:10,561 --> 00:28:12,051
witch !

234
00:28:13,097 --> 00:28:15,361
she's a daughter of the devil!

235
00:28:15,733 --> 00:28:19,567
- a demon has got her!
- she's ill!

236
00:28:19,937 --> 00:28:24,033
she's not possessed!

237
00:28:29,780 --> 00:28:31,179
burn her!

238
00:28:35,419 --> 00:28:38,445
she mustn't swallow her tongue.
she'd suffocate.

239
00:28:39,790 --> 00:28:43,954
- she's not possessed.
- l know.

240
00:28:53,771 --> 00:28:57,730
naturalist, philosopher
and a bonesetter as well?

241
00:29:08,485 --> 00:29:11,079
she didn't show. l won the bet.

242
00:29:20,464 --> 00:29:21,658
Marquis.

243
00:29:33,711 --> 00:29:35,303
and the natives?

244
00:29:37,414 --> 00:29:40,315
superstitious brutes, like here.

245
00:29:41,885 --> 00:29:46,379
lndian hunters eat the hearts
of their prey for strength.

246
00:29:46,523 --> 00:29:48,423
are they brutes then?

247
00:29:48,559 --> 00:29:51,824
ln africa, it's their enemies' hearts.

248
00:29:52,229 --> 00:29:56,825
My lord the count, jean-francois,
you must move east...

249
00:29:58,035 --> 00:29:59,400
there you are.

250
00:29:59,603 --> 00:30:02,299
your mother will be worried.

251
00:30:02,673 --> 00:30:06,973
she always is.
lf l listened, l'd be in a convent.

252
00:30:07,411 --> 00:30:10,471
l knew you didn't believe me.
you're a libertine.

253
00:30:10,648 --> 00:30:14,049
- not when l'm in love.
- you're in love?

254
00:30:19,023 --> 00:30:22,151
ridiculous! we've hardly met.

255
00:30:23,060 --> 00:30:25,119
you thought l meant you?

256
00:30:32,603 --> 00:30:35,629
she must learn to ride like a lady.

257
00:30:36,607 --> 00:30:39,201
no harm in a little exercise.

258
00:30:41,979 --> 00:30:46,006
- My father sees no evil.
- My son sees evil everywhere.

259
00:31:42,106 --> 00:31:44,233
people died here.

260
00:31:45,309 --> 00:31:46,799
how do you know?

261
00:31:48,645 --> 00:31:50,078
l hear their cries.

262
00:31:50,481 --> 00:31:52,210
Mani, stop it.

263
00:31:52,416 --> 00:31:56,147
he's right. this was a templar stronghold.

264
00:31:56,987 --> 00:32:00,286
twenty-five heretics
were burned alive in the chapel.

265
00:32:01,625 --> 00:32:05,254
- ls he a seer?
- no need to be.

266
00:32:09,767 --> 00:32:11,564
you just need to look.

267
00:32:21,745 --> 00:32:24,213
My brother and l played here.

268
00:32:24,848 --> 00:32:26,543
were you not afraid?

269
00:32:28,152 --> 00:32:30,518
he said he would protect me from ghosts.

270
00:33:43,060 --> 00:33:47,087
- no taste for the hunt?
- that a crime here?

271
00:33:49,666 --> 00:33:52,931
the lndians say
a portrait steals the soul.

272
00:33:53,704 --> 00:33:55,797
My soul interests you as well?

273
00:34:38,815 --> 00:34:40,908
on foot at a hunt?

274
00:34:41,084 --> 00:34:44,178
- My fault.
- l didn't ask you.

275
00:34:46,757 --> 00:34:50,090
- what possessed you?
- lt's only a wolf.

276
00:34:50,394 --> 00:34:53,989
- and if it were the beast?
- l don't think so.

277
00:34:58,435 --> 00:34:59,697
thank you.

278
00:35:06,944 --> 00:35:10,107
pray the beast is one of these wolves.

279
00:35:10,280 --> 00:35:13,044
these won't devour anyone now.

280
00:35:14,751 --> 00:35:16,218
curious fellow.

281
00:35:16,787 --> 00:35:19,449
- where did you find him?
- new france.

282
00:35:20,824 --> 00:35:23,156
ls he an acadian?

283
00:35:23,627 --> 00:35:26,619
an lndian. a Mohawk lroquois.

284
00:35:26,930 --> 00:35:31,424
an lndian? a real one?
he doesn't look it.

285
00:35:31,969 --> 00:35:36,963
come to st. alban tonight.
we'll have fun with your valet.

286
00:35:37,107 --> 00:35:38,802
he's not my valet.

287
00:35:38,942 --> 00:35:41,672
- what then?
- he's my brother.

288
00:36:04,301 --> 00:36:09,000
really! Mixing your blood
with that of a savage?

289
00:36:10,307 --> 00:36:13,105
a man who shares one's hardship
is no savage.

290
00:36:13,744 --> 00:36:16,804
Mani saved me from the english
at trois rivieres.

291
00:36:17,180 --> 00:36:19,876
l thought the savages were cannibals.

292
00:36:20,150 --> 00:36:24,314
as you can see, sir, Mani is no animal.

293
00:36:28,291 --> 00:36:32,022
can you reproduce
with a woman of our race?

294
00:36:35,065 --> 00:36:39,263
all women are the same color
when candles blow out.

295
00:36:39,936 --> 00:36:42,336
yes, father, they even have wit.

296
00:36:42,672 --> 00:36:45,368
lndians and whites have had children.

297
00:36:45,509 --> 00:36:47,704
we're one species.

298
00:36:47,844 --> 00:36:51,575
don't speak too soon.
lt's a bit like the negroes.

299
00:36:52,949 --> 00:36:54,780
what say you, sardis?

300
00:36:55,152 --> 00:36:58,053
your blood brother is god's child.

301
00:36:58,455 --> 00:37:00,889
- has he been baptized?
- he hasn't asked.

302
00:37:01,024 --> 00:37:03,219
you are a man of your times!

303
00:37:03,360 --> 00:37:05,260
Mani has his beliefs.

304
00:37:05,395 --> 00:37:09,422
at home, he was a sort of priest.

305
00:37:10,067 --> 00:37:13,332
lf they have priests, they're doomed.

306
00:37:13,470 --> 00:37:15,199
what are these beliefs?

307
00:37:15,338 --> 00:37:19,331
each man has an animal spirit,
called a totem.

308
00:37:19,976 --> 00:37:21,705
amusing. how does it work?

309
00:37:25,115 --> 00:37:26,446
would you?

310
00:37:35,992 --> 00:37:38,256
never fear, it won't hurt.

311
00:37:48,171 --> 00:37:51,299
caribou. a sort of stag.

312
00:37:53,110 --> 00:37:54,873
what says my wife?

313
00:37:55,011 --> 00:37:59,277
am l a stag because of my horns
or because of something else?

314
00:38:00,083 --> 00:38:04,019
and my dear thomas, what's his totem?

315
00:38:04,254 --> 00:38:06,449
worm. bookworm probably.

316
00:38:15,599 --> 00:38:16,588
snake.

317
00:38:17,801 --> 00:38:20,326
for lndians, the snake embodies wisdom.

318
00:38:20,470 --> 00:38:21,869
serpent wise.

319
00:38:22,205 --> 00:38:23,832
and our intendant?

320
00:38:28,245 --> 00:38:29,405
boar.

321
00:38:31,214 --> 00:38:32,647
lighten your spirit.

322
00:38:33,083 --> 00:38:37,144
perhaps for these barbarians
the pig is nobility.

323
00:38:37,954 --> 00:38:39,717
who's next? sardis?

324
00:38:45,362 --> 00:38:46,522
and me?

325
00:38:47,664 --> 00:38:50,428
what am l, a semi-lion?

326
00:38:51,268 --> 00:38:52,758
half an eagle?

327
00:38:54,171 --> 00:38:57,732
Make me a lizard,
so my arm may grow back.

328
00:38:57,941 --> 00:38:59,841
jean-francois, enough.

329
00:39:02,879 --> 00:39:05,279
what? have l been gauche?

330
00:39:06,983 --> 00:39:09,679
let me be.

331
00:39:10,587 --> 00:39:12,987
Mademoiselle? your turn?

332
00:39:14,691 --> 00:39:17,854
pardon me,
but l'm weary of your tricks.

333
00:39:17,994 --> 00:39:22,192
l'll retire before you begin
juggling or dancing on a ball.

334
00:39:22,332 --> 00:39:23,731
good night.

335
00:39:44,221 --> 00:39:46,212
lt'll cheer you, fronsac.

336
00:39:46,356 --> 00:39:51,293
lt's the best house in Mende.
you'll sleep better than at an inn.

337
00:40:04,674 --> 00:40:08,542
they're all for you.
and the new girl is very...

338
00:40:10,981 --> 00:40:12,710
dear little Marquis.

339
00:40:13,183 --> 00:40:14,343
come.

340
00:40:59,396 --> 00:41:02,456
l'm expensive, gregoire de fronsac.

341
00:41:02,899 --> 00:41:07,529
- do you know me?
- ln here, gevaudan becomes very small.

342
00:41:08,471 --> 00:41:09,733
ltalian?

343
00:41:11,508 --> 00:41:13,442
just passing through.

344
00:41:15,679 --> 00:41:17,237
l have money.

345
00:41:17,947 --> 00:41:21,474
lt's not only a matter of money.

346
00:41:29,659 --> 00:41:31,183
what then?

347
00:41:54,217 --> 00:41:59,120
- who did that to you?
- an lroquois arrow.

348
00:42:00,290 --> 00:42:02,281
not far from the heart.

349
00:42:03,226 --> 00:42:06,718
l may be a lucky man.

350
00:42:08,998 --> 00:42:10,329
and that?

351
00:42:12,669 --> 00:42:13,829
a bear.

352
00:42:15,605 --> 00:42:18,096
he didn't care much for me.

353
00:42:26,683 --> 00:42:29,208
you haven't seen anything yet.

354
00:42:43,600 --> 00:42:45,898
My business is dangerous.

355
00:42:47,303 --> 00:42:49,362
some men aren't so nice.

356
00:42:54,544 --> 00:42:57,138
something to remember me by.

357
00:43:01,751 --> 00:43:04,151
a scandal! ln my house!

358
00:43:05,922 --> 00:43:08,823
- valentine!
- l don't lay with sorcerers!

359
00:43:08,958 --> 00:43:11,791
- what?
- snakes on him! l saw them move!

360
00:43:11,928 --> 00:43:14,362
our reputation ! you have to go!

361
00:43:14,497 --> 00:43:17,955
lt's nothing.
he's an lndian, not a sorcerer.

362
00:43:18,101 --> 00:43:21,366
- then no lndians!
- you have delicate whores.

363
00:43:22,138 --> 00:43:25,665
come on, girls.
who will go with our redskin?

364
00:43:26,276 --> 00:43:28,471
l'll double the fee.

365
00:43:28,845 --> 00:43:32,872
- l like his tattoos.
- that settles that.

366
00:43:33,850 --> 00:43:37,013
so, a sorcerer are we?

367
00:44:26,469 --> 00:44:28,334
will you do my portrait?

368
00:44:29,038 --> 00:44:30,835
lf you don't behave.

369
00:44:49,192 --> 00:44:53,788
weekspassed, and duhamel's men
xouldn't find the beast,

370
00:44:55,198 --> 00:44:58,725
a third winter would be spent
underits reign,

371
00:44:59,269 --> 00:45:04,138
the snow xould not stop it
anymore than ourrifles and dogs,

372
00:45:09,312 --> 00:45:13,715
recall how god warned us
through the words of Moses:

373
00:45:15,386 --> 00:45:19,652
''l shall xome unto you like a bear
whose xubs are ravished,

374
00:45:21,592 --> 00:45:26,154
''as a lion l shall devour your children
and spill their entrails.

375
00:45:27,498 --> 00:45:30,228
''l will set upon ye a fearsome beast

376
00:45:30,367 --> 00:45:33,336
''to consume you and your flocks,

377
00:45:33,471 --> 00:45:36,099
''and make your fields barren.''

378
00:45:44,949 --> 00:45:49,409
how long, o lord, wouldst thou forsake us?

379
00:46:12,110 --> 00:46:17,047
a candle for each victim.
ls this truly the age of reason?

380
00:46:32,096 --> 00:46:33,688
have mercy!

381
00:46:35,199 --> 00:46:36,461
forgive me!

382
00:46:37,502 --> 00:46:38,730
have mercy!

383
00:46:40,672 --> 00:46:42,071
bless me!

384
00:46:46,744 --> 00:46:48,405
what is it, my son?

385
00:46:48,546 --> 00:46:52,073
god has punished me!
My children vanished on Mt. Mouchet!

386
00:46:52,383 --> 00:46:55,284
l'm damned! we all are!

387
00:46:58,255 --> 00:47:01,088
gather your men. we must leave.

388
00:47:07,164 --> 00:47:09,394
alert Mani. l'll find you on the way!

389
00:47:17,842 --> 00:47:19,776
hello, friend of the wolves.

390
00:47:20,010 --> 00:47:22,240
l have something for you.

391
00:47:28,452 --> 00:47:31,717
l want to see you. alone.

392
00:47:34,859 --> 00:47:39,296
ln 10 days my mother's going to a retreat
and my father to a cure.

393
00:47:39,430 --> 00:47:42,866
- ten days?
- l'm not as free as you.

394
00:49:07,718 --> 00:49:08,912
the torch.

395
00:49:10,154 --> 00:49:11,621
bring the torch !

396
00:49:16,594 --> 00:49:19,188
the storm is rising; the men are tired.

397
00:49:19,496 --> 00:49:20,827
we'd best go home.

398
00:49:21,732 --> 00:49:23,996
no. we must find the girl.

399
00:50:05,242 --> 00:50:06,903
l found the child.

400
00:50:25,729 --> 00:50:30,666
captain, your web of traps
snares more peasants than wolves,

401
00:50:31,502 --> 00:50:34,801
your men have plundered the population,

402
00:50:35,472 --> 00:50:39,772
and since you began,
the wolf has taken 12 more lives.

403
00:50:40,210 --> 00:50:43,179
lt should never have escaped us.

404
00:50:43,314 --> 00:50:44,440
how's that?

405
00:50:44,581 --> 00:50:47,516
lt should never have escaped us.

406
00:50:47,685 --> 00:50:49,312
what say you, fronsac?

407
00:50:50,020 --> 00:50:52,648
what sort of wolf is this?

408
00:50:58,028 --> 00:51:01,794
My only certainty is that this is no wolf.

409
00:51:02,666 --> 00:51:07,535
wolves don't attack men, or very rarely.
l studied them in new france.

410
00:51:07,671 --> 00:51:10,572
perhaps our wolves are different.

411
00:51:10,708 --> 00:51:12,801
a rabid wolf will attack.

412
00:51:13,377 --> 00:51:15,902
and dies within a fortnight.

413
00:51:16,046 --> 00:51:18,913
for two years,
the beast has had its bloody reign.

414
00:51:19,550 --> 00:51:23,042
lts victims bear wounds
no wolf could inflict.

415
00:51:24,621 --> 00:51:28,022
l've often found upon the body

416
00:51:28,158 --> 00:51:30,149
a piece of this metal.

417
00:51:30,694 --> 00:51:33,185
- so?
- so...

418
00:51:35,666 --> 00:51:38,396
no animal has fangs of iron.

419
00:51:42,639 --> 00:51:45,631
then the beast is not an animal? fine.

420
00:51:46,610 --> 00:51:48,043
how do we catch it?

421
00:51:48,178 --> 00:51:50,908
while we speculate,
it's killing our people.

422
00:51:51,415 --> 00:51:55,909
gentlemen, let us hear M. de fronsac
with utmost attention.

423
00:51:57,654 --> 00:51:59,747
so you say, sir,

424
00:51:59,923 --> 00:52:02,824
this is no ordinary animal.

425
00:52:03,660 --> 00:52:05,025
we all think so.

426
00:52:05,462 --> 00:52:08,625
and for myself l'm pleased you concede

427
00:52:08,766 --> 00:52:11,701
this is something supernatural.

428
00:52:11,835 --> 00:52:15,669
l concede nothing, father.
l have only doubts.

429
00:52:16,440 --> 00:52:18,635
anything to add?

430
00:52:19,943 --> 00:52:21,308
no, gentlemen.

431
00:52:23,213 --> 00:52:26,011
l've received this from paris.

432
00:52:27,217 --> 00:52:32,154
capt. duhamel his Majesty has been
informed of your ineffective efforts.

433
00:52:33,257 --> 00:52:36,283
he requests you be
relieved of your duties.

434
00:52:36,760 --> 00:52:40,787
you and your men
are to return to langogne at once.

435
00:52:41,532 --> 00:52:44,763
sir beauterne, Master at arms,
is on his way.

436
00:52:44,902 --> 00:52:48,394
his mandate is to kill
this ferocious wolf.

437
00:52:49,840 --> 00:52:53,833
he alone is authorized to hunt
in the diocese.

438
00:52:55,345 --> 00:52:56,642
gentlemen.

439
00:53:09,159 --> 00:53:10,922
then l'm forgiven?

440
00:53:11,395 --> 00:53:15,195
l was curious to know my ''totem''.
ls that the word?

441
00:53:15,332 --> 00:53:16,856
l would guess...

442
00:53:18,268 --> 00:53:19,462
mermaid.

443
00:53:20,070 --> 00:53:23,733
are you never serious?
l'll ask your redskin.

444
00:53:25,042 --> 00:53:27,875
and the beast? have you spotted it?

445
00:53:29,213 --> 00:53:30,680
forbidden subject?

446
00:53:30,814 --> 00:53:35,251
My absurd assumptions would
get me laughed out of king's garden.

447
00:53:35,986 --> 00:53:39,922
lf l said the beast
is flesh and iron mixed,

448
00:53:40,457 --> 00:53:44,791
that it's possessed of reason
and may disappear at will,

449
00:53:44,928 --> 00:53:46,225
what would you say?

450
00:53:46,363 --> 00:53:49,161
country air has affected your mind.

451
00:53:49,299 --> 00:53:50,926
lt's eluding me.

452
00:53:51,335 --> 00:53:55,135
after three months,
you expect to have finished?

453
00:53:55,272 --> 00:54:00,209
should the beast have surrendered?
perhaps it's afraid of you.

454
00:54:00,844 --> 00:54:02,471
am l so fearsome?

455
00:54:02,613 --> 00:54:05,810
a hard-won victory will be better savored.

456
00:54:08,352 --> 00:54:11,253
ls it true you're going to africa?

457
00:54:11,622 --> 00:54:15,285
for now it's but
a naturalist's winter dream.

458
00:54:15,425 --> 00:54:18,656
and you? ever yearn for new horizons?

459
00:54:20,597 --> 00:54:23,964
a lady has more duties than yearnings.

460
00:54:24,101 --> 00:54:26,661
do you see sardis over there?

461
00:54:27,604 --> 00:54:29,196
are you being watched?

462
00:54:30,607 --> 00:54:32,302
he's there to protect me.

463
00:54:32,442 --> 00:54:36,105
alone with you,
god knows what could happen.

464
00:54:36,613 --> 00:54:40,572
let's go inside.
our priest might catch cold.

465
00:54:51,428 --> 00:54:53,020
good evening, sir.

466
00:55:05,542 --> 00:55:08,534
- you're in love.
- l don't know.

467
00:55:09,079 --> 00:55:10,546
l do.

468
00:55:11,148 --> 00:55:12,410
the cards?

469
00:55:12,883 --> 00:55:15,647
l've never needed them for you.

470
00:55:17,287 --> 00:55:19,221
so let's drink.

471
00:55:21,091 --> 00:55:23,616
to Mademoiselle de Morangias.

472
00:55:25,028 --> 00:55:28,395
- what?
- her brother was here.

473
00:55:29,600 --> 00:55:31,431
you slept with him?

474
00:55:33,337 --> 00:55:36,773
him? he can't stand to be touched.

475
00:55:37,808 --> 00:55:40,333
he watches, he drinks,

476
00:55:40,777 --> 00:55:44,577
then he talks in his sleep, like all men.

477
00:55:45,716 --> 00:55:47,149
do l?

478
00:55:48,852 --> 00:55:50,376
what do l say?

479
00:55:51,321 --> 00:55:52,788
''again !''

480
00:55:59,529 --> 00:56:03,727
know how florentine women
keep their husbands home?

481
00:56:06,803 --> 00:56:09,499
each morning, they give them

482
00:56:09,773 --> 00:56:12,241
a slow poison,

483
00:56:12,843 --> 00:56:15,038
and every evening the antidote.

484
00:56:15,178 --> 00:56:18,614
that way, when the husband sleeps away

485
00:56:18,749 --> 00:56:20,910
he has a very bad night.

486
00:56:22,786 --> 00:56:25,050
you needn't resort to that.

487
00:56:29,626 --> 00:56:32,288
anyway, we aren't married.

488
00:57:58,515 --> 00:58:02,952
Make way for antoine de beauterne,
royal Master at arms,

489
00:58:03,086 --> 00:58:06,544
who has come to rid the country
of the beast!

490
00:58:26,977 --> 00:58:31,073
- l am gregoire de fronsac.
- yes, buffon's envoy.

491
00:58:31,214 --> 00:58:33,011
the naturalist embalmer.

492
00:58:33,150 --> 00:58:37,211
M. de beauterne is at the lntendant's.
come at 2:00.

493
00:59:17,194 --> 00:59:21,153
his Majesty asked my advice
about your report.

494
00:59:22,265 --> 00:59:24,563
complicated fables indeed!

495
00:59:25,869 --> 00:59:29,032
l believe the beast is a wolf.

496
00:59:32,209 --> 00:59:35,201
l shall go out for it tomorrow.

497
00:59:35,345 --> 00:59:38,178
l would rather you didn't come.

498
00:59:41,585 --> 00:59:42,916
why is that?

499
00:59:44,521 --> 00:59:49,117
the king left this affair to me,
and to my sole discretion.

500
00:59:50,060 --> 00:59:52,824
l have no need of you to end it.

501
00:59:57,334 --> 01:00:02,203
on the table there's a letter
from buffon and our beloved king.

502
01:00:04,107 --> 01:00:07,975
l'm at his service,
but believe me this is not--

503
01:00:08,111 --> 01:00:12,548
l've read your report. trouble yourself
no longer with this beast.

504
01:00:12,682 --> 01:00:14,274
lt's my affair.

505
01:00:16,419 --> 01:00:17,681
you may go.

506
01:00:23,527 --> 01:00:25,051
come here.

507
01:01:40,136 --> 01:01:44,004
a woman from lorxiere,
lt attaxked her xoming from the fair,

